00:00:00.849 --> 00:00:04.210
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Thanks for joining us
for today's Green at Google Talk. My name

00:00:04.210 --> 00:00:09.150
is Alice Mount and I work on data center environmental
health and safety. It's with great pleasure

00:00:09.150 --> 00:00:13.410
and excitement that I introduce our three
speakers. Although each has a very different

00:00:13.410 --> 00:00:18.670
background, they're here today with something
in common. The desire to address climate change,

00:00:18.670 --> 00:00:23.210
environmental pollution and energy security
through the promise of renewable energy.

00:00:23.210 --> 00:00:27.699
Going in alphabetical order, Mark Jacobson
is the Director of Atmosphere/Energy Program

00:00:27.699 --> 00:00:32.879
and Professor of Civil and Environmental Engineering
at Stanford University. He is also a Senior

00:00:32.879 --> 00:00:38.260
Fellow of the Woods Institute for the Environment.
And a Senior Fellow of the Precourt Institute

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:42.969
for Energy. He is on the Energy Efficiency
and Renewable Environment committee for the

00:00:42.969 --> 00:00:47.949
US Secretary of Energy. And he was my advisor
at Stanford. [laughter]

00:00:47.949 --> 00:00:52.609
Marco Krapels is the Executive Vice President
of Rabobank North America, where he runs the

00:00:52.609 --> 00:00:57.100
commercial banking product groups, including
its capital markets and renewable energy finance

00:00:57.100 --> 00:01:02.050
divisions. He co-chairs the bank's Corporate
Social Responsibility committee where he's

00:01:02.050 --> 00:01:07.579
initiated notable sustainability efforts including
a Rabobank solar/Tesla electric car project

00:01:07.579 --> 00:01:12.840
featured in the New York Times. Marco is co-founder
and board member of Empowered by Light which

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:18.909
promotes renewable energy solutions for one
point six billion people living without electricity.

00:01:18.909 --> 00:01:23.759
And last, but certainly not least, Mark Ruffalo
is an Oscar-nominated actor and renewable

00:01:23.759 --> 00:01:29.400
energy advocate. In March 2011, Marco founded
Water Defense to raise awareness about the

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:35.719
impact of energy extraction on water and public
health. A regular contributor to the Guardian

00:01:35.719 --> 00:01:41.340
and the Huffington Post, Mark is a recent
recipient of the Global Green Millennium Award

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:46.649
for Environmental Leadership. Most recently,
he played Dr. Banner and the Incredible Hulk

00:01:46.649 --> 00:01:52.990
in the Avengers. I will hold back on making
any green puns. I wouldn't wanna make him

00:01:52.990 --> 00:01:54.000
angry.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:55.020
[laughter]

00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:58.600
Thanks for coming and welcome to Google. For
those of you who would like to ask questions,

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:04.289
we have a Google moderator page set up at
'go wind water sun'. Thank you.

00:02:04.289 --> 00:02:06.159
[applause]

00:02:06.159 --> 00:02:16.640
&gt;&gt;Mark Ruffalo: Thank you for that introduction.
You wouldn't like me when I'm angry.

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:17.740
[laughter]

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:25.550
Wow. Thank you Google for having us here.
I'm more nervous about this than I am any

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:35.420
of that acting stuff I do. I wanna start by
how I got here. I really don't wanna be here

00:02:35.420 --> 00:02:36.420
today.

00:02:36.420 --> 00:02:37.420
[laughter]

00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:42.330
I'd rather be at home with my kids today.
Running in the sprinkler. It's the first day

00:02:42.330 --> 00:02:52.070
of summer. But three years ago I made the,
I guess, fortunate or unfortunate decision

00:02:52.070 --> 00:02:59.030
to move my family to upstate New York where
they can live with trees and flowers and chirping

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:07.060
birds and clean water and fresh air. And shortly
after moving there I found out that this incredible

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:15.780
thing called hydrofracking was going to happen
in my community. And when I first heard about

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:22.270
it, I thought it was the greatest thing since
sliced bread. It was gonna give us energy

00:03:22.270 --> 00:03:30.340
independence. It was clean. It was cheap.
All it was was injecting a little sand and

00:03:30.340 --> 00:03:39.420
water into the ground and it was going to
free us from war, pestilence, viruses, the

00:03:39.420 --> 00:03:42.740
Plague, and Satan himself.

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:44.010
[laughter]

00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:51.650
That sounded great to me. So I'm the type
of person, I'm a very simple man and decided

00:03:51.650 --> 00:03:57.460
that I would go online and check out what
exactly hydrofracking was. And as I started

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:03.630
looking into it, I started seeing there was
a lot of problems with it. Like people being

00:04:03.630 --> 00:04:09.050
able to light their wells on fire. And coming
down with brain lesions. And their well caps

00:04:09.050 --> 00:04:14.600
blowing 50, 60 feet into the air. And their
water becoming contaminated. And their children

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:22.720
developing asthma. And spills. And their pets
and livestock dying or going bald or becoming

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:29.210
ill. And those things didn't sound like white
bread to me.

00:04:29.210 --> 00:04:34.100
And I realized that maybe hydrofracking was
more relatable to asbestos, the greatest thing

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:41.990
since asbestos than white bread. If you remember
when we had our beginning love affair with

00:04:41.990 --> 00:04:46.010
asbestos, it was the greatest thing that could
ever have happened to us. It was gonna change

00:04:46.010 --> 00:04:52.760
our world. It was gonna make jobs for us.
And it was just this incredible thing. And

00:04:52.760 --> 00:05:01.231
in time we've come to find out that it isn't
so incredible. So I began basically, I went

00:05:01.231 --> 00:05:07.360
to Dimick, PA with Robert Kennedy, Junior
and I saw a group of people, probably 40 people,

00:05:07.360 --> 00:05:15.280
who had their wells contaminated with natural
gas from hydrofracking. And there was no one

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:20.400
there to help them. And they literally looked
at Robert Kennedy Junior as if he was Jesus

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:27.740
Christ himself and walked across the water
to save them. Unfortunately at that time,

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:34.760
Robert Kennedy Junior had been toking off
the natural gas pipe and was a big natural

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:42.960
gas advocate. It's taken us two years to turn
him around. But, by God, we have. Us and science

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:49.590
and a lot of compelling anecdotal evidence
that tell us that this is not the way to move

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:53.260
forward.

00:05:53.260 --> 00:06:02.620
But when I was there, I had family after family
come up to me and since I was the B-list celebrity

00:06:02.620 --> 00:06:09.300
in the room, behind Robert Kennedy, Junior,
I was the next savior. Something on par to

00:06:09.300 --> 00:06:18.830
probably Houdini more than Jesus Christ. But
I recognized an enormous need that they had

00:06:18.830 --> 00:06:24.680
that wasn't being filled, neither by their
legislative body in the state of Pennsylvania

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:31.530
nor by the EPA which had been exempt, this
industry had been exempted from any federal

00:06:31.530 --> 00:06:41.050
regulation. And they were asking for my help.
And I decided that I would run as far away

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:44.620
from them as I possibly could.

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:49.830
But I couldn't run away from myself. And I
realized that I wouldn't be the human being

00:06:49.830 --> 00:06:56.240
that I say I am, if I turned my back on them.
Essentially I'd be turning my back on my own

00:06:56.240 --> 00:07:03.940
children and my own community just across
the Delaware River. And so I began fighting

00:07:03.940 --> 00:07:13.070
hydrofracking in New York State. And at some
point that wasn't enough for me. I felt like

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:19.500
you can't really be effective at fighting
something unless you can come up with an alternative

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:29.820
to that thing, that was viable, and that was
credible. And so in my very, I like to model

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:36.510
myself after Percival the Fool, I went like
the fool into the world saying "I don't know

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:40.960
what the hell I'm doing or what I'm talking
about, but I'd like to go find some people

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:49.120
that do know what they're doing and what they're
talking about. And I was invited to go to

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:53.790
the Global Green Awards, which I didn't wanna
get an award for this work. I went kicking

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:58.580
and screaming. They wanted to honor me with
an environmental award. I didn't feel like

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:07.729
I deserved it. But I didn't wanna be an asshole,
so I went. And while I was there, shortly

00:08:07.729 --> 00:08:15.270
after I gave my speech on natural gas to a
very large group of people who at that time

00:08:15.270 --> 00:08:24.380
still believed that natural gas was the answer.
And I was there to say "No." Well, after it,

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:30.740
this crazy Dutchman came up to me and he said
"Hi, I'm Marcellus. And I'm here to help you

00:08:30.740 --> 00:08:35.969
fight Marcellus." Now Marcellus Shale is where
in New York where they wanna extract the gas

00:08:35.969 --> 00:08:45.709
from. And Marco Krapels real name is Marcellus.
And I kinda, he said "You know, we have to

00:08:45.709 --> 00:08:52.180
talk about the solutions." Like I kinda had
said well, I wanna do this crazy thing, I

00:08:52.180 --> 00:08:58.480
wanna, why aren't we going to renewable, why
are we gonna go to natural gas and then renewable.

00:08:58.480 --> 00:09:04.040
I mean why not go directly to renewables.
Like why do we have to bridge to it? Like

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:10.949
why don't we hang-glide over it? And he said
"Come to California, I'm gonna put together

00:09:10.949 --> 00:09:19.230
some meetings. We're doing this here and I
think you can do it in New York." And he brought

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:28.279
me to a dinner and at that dinner was Professor
Mark Jacobson. And a lot of other really influential

00:09:28.279 --> 00:09:35.149
people in the renewable space. And what I
started to hear was what I believed in my

00:09:35.149 --> 00:09:40.619
heart. Was that we actually could make this
transition. Without introducing an entire

00:09:40.619 --> 00:09:48.749
new fossil fuel infrastructure to our nation
that would cost us 700 billion dollars to

00:09:48.749 --> 00:09:56.399
build out. And we actually could hang glide
over natural gas and move directly to renewable

00:09:56.399 --> 00:10:07.679
energy. And we could do it in my lifetime.
And that was the beginning of this journey.

00:10:07.679 --> 00:10:13.760
And along this journey I only knew that the
only thing that I could offer to these brilliant

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:25.689
people was that I was a conduit of information
to my culture. To the culture. And we're in

00:10:25.689 --> 00:10:32.820
an information war. Really is what this is
about. It's about education. Because the truth

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:44.350
is that we can do this. We're technologically
poised to do it. But there's an enormous political

00:10:44.350 --> 00:10:55.470
lobbying structure in place in this country
that is telling us that we can't do it. And

00:10:55.470 --> 00:11:03.579
that we are bound to be a fossil fuel nation
for another 50, 60, 100 years. And that just

00:11:03.579 --> 00:11:05.870
isn't the truth.

00:11:05.870 --> 00:11:17.769
And so I started to try and make myself knowledged
in what the truth was. By going to scientists.

00:11:17.769 --> 00:11:25.600
Going to business leaders, going to bankers,
and asking "Is this possible? And how do we

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:34.779
do it?" And that was basically how I came
to be sitting here with these two extraordinary

00:11:34.779 --> 00:11:41.119
gentlemen. There's another gentleman here
named Jon Wank from Skadaddle who is basically

00:11:41.119 --> 00:11:48.880
our media genius. And we figure that if you
can handle the science and the culture and

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:54.610
the banking and the economics and then have
a platform to get the message out, we actually

00:11:54.610 --> 00:12:02.209
have a chance of making this thing happen.
And so the idea of solutions was born.

00:12:02.209 --> 00:12:09.959
And none of us are on the payroll of anybody.
We all flew ourselves here today. We are only

00:12:09.959 --> 00:12:16.230
compelled to move forward with this mission
because we have children. And we believe that

00:12:16.230 --> 00:12:22.519
it's the right and responsible thing for each
of us to do. And that gives us an enormous

00:12:22.519 --> 00:12:29.240
amount of credibility in the face of who our
opponent is and the enormous amount of political

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:36.139
and economic power that they wield against
us. And so, at this moment, I would gladly

00:12:36.139 --> 00:12:37.850
like to shut up.

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:38.850
[laughter]

